    <h3>Pool and Spa Chemicals</h3>
    <p>Pool owners regularly convert between gallons and ounces when dosing chemicals. Chlorine, algaecide, pH adjusters, and clarifiers are typically measured in fluid ounces per 10,000 gallons of pool water. If your pool holds 15,000 gallons and the chlorine label says "add 6 fluid ounces per 10,000 gallons," you need 9 fluid ounces. Hot tub chemicals are dosed per gallon — a 400-gallon spa holds 51,200 fluid ounces, but you measure additives in small fluid ounce amounts relative to the total volume.</p>

    <h3>Fuel and Automotive</h3>
    <p>Gasoline is sold by the gallon in the United States. When comparing fuel efficiency between US and UK vehicles, remember that UK miles per gallon figures use the larger imperial gallon. A car rated at 40 mpg in the UK is equivalent to about 33.3 mpg using US gallons. Engine oil, transmission fluid, and coolant are often measured in quarts (32 ounces each). A typical oil change requires 4 to 6 quarts (128 to 192 ounces, or 1 to 1.5 gallons).</p>

    <h2>Converting Liters to Gallons and Ounces</h2>
